    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan. 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Will you be so good as to give orders for the immediate printing off of copies of the Diagram for the new Edit. of the Origin.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> The new Edit will be (with Index) I think 448 pages; &amp; as it has no illustrations, do you not think 6<hi rend="superscript">s</hi> is too dear for a cheap Edit? Would not 5<hi rend="superscript">s</hi> be better?<ref target="#foot.f3"/> Pray think of this. The public are accustomed to novels for 1<hi rend="superscript">s</hi>.—</p>
<p>Yours sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p>
<p>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Dallas has made an excellent Glossary.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.1 immediate] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">3.1 M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> … Glossary.—] <hi rend="italic">added in margin</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the references to the sixth edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref>, which was published in 1872.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">A fold-out diagram of species descent was included in all editions of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref>; in the sixth edition it faced page 90.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6019.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 6th ed.</ref> was 458 pages long with 21 pages of preliminaries. It sold for 7<hi rend="italic">s.</hi> 6<hi rend="italic">d.</hi> The first and fifth edition had sold for 15<hi rend="italic">s.</hi>, and the second, third, and fourth for 14<hi rend="italic">s.</hi> (Peckham ed. 1959, pp. 16–22).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6019.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 6th ed.</ref> included for the first time a glossary by <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1179.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Sweetland Dallas</ref> (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 19, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8007.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to R. F. Cooke, 13 October [1871]</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
